      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While the moral imperative for healthcare access is clear, the \"inefficiency\" argument is a political talking point, not a factual refutation of the right to care. The reality is that the \"efficiency\" of a system is measured by its ability to keep citizens healthy, which universal systems demonstrably achieve better than fragmented private models. Therefore, the argument against universal care is often a defense of market ideology over human dignity.",
